ack Machine</a><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Webarchive_template_wayback_links" about="#mwt370" id="mwBAc"/></i>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-63" id="cite_note-63"><a href="./Addition#cite_ref-63" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-63" class="mw-reference-text">The intuitive approach, inverting every element of a cut and taking its complement, works only for irrational numbers; see Enderton p. 117 for details.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-64" id="cite_note-64"><a href="./Addition#cite_ref-64" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-64" class="mw-reference-text">Schubert, E. Thomas, Phillip J. Windley, and James Alves-Foss. "Higher Order Logic Theorem Proving and Its Applications: Proceedings of the 8th International Workshop, volume 971 of." <i id="mwBAg">Lecture Notes in Computer Science</i> (1995).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-65" id="cite_note-65"><a href="./Addition#cite_ref-65" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-65" class="mw-reference-text">Textbook constructions are usually not so cavalier with the "lim" symbol; see Burrill (p. 138) for a more careful, drawn-out development of addition with Cauchy sequences.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-66" id="cite_note-66"><a href="./Addition#cite_ref-66" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-66" class="mw-reference-text">Ferreirós p. 128</span></li><li about="#cite_note-67" id="cite_note-67"><a href="./Addition#cite_ref-67" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-67" class="mw-reference-text">Burrill p. 140</span></li><li about="#cite_note-68" id="cite_note-68"><a href="./Addition#cite_ref-68" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span><